Hungary Stocks Gain Most in 3 Weeks on G-7; Mol, OTP Advance

-- B y   A n d r a s   G e r g e l y
-- 
2011-03-17T16:58:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-17/hungary-stocks-gain-most-in-two-weeks-on-g-7-otp-bank-advances.html
Hungarian shares rose the most in
three weeks on speculation Group of Seven officials will act to
calm markets roiled by  Japan ’s nuclear disaster and as rising
crude oil prices supported Mol Nyrt.  The benchmark BUX index rose 1.7 percent to 22,280.31 by
the 5 p.m. close in Budapest, the biggest daily gain since Feb.
25, after falling as much as 0.5 percent earlier today.  Mol Nyrt., the country’s largest refiner, gained 3.5
percent to 23,500 forint and OTP Bank Nyrt., the country’s
biggest lender, rose 2.3 percent. Mol accounts for 33 percent of
the BUX’s weighting and OTP for 31 percent.  Group of Seven officials will meet tomorrow to discuss the
nuclear threat developing from the 9-magnitude earthquake in
Japan, raising the prospect of coordinated action to prevent the
disaster from crippling the world’s third-largest economy. Crude
oil climbed 2.9 percent to $100.86 a barrel in  New York  on
concern that unrest in North Africa and the Middle East will
spread, reducing shipments from the region.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Andras Gergely in Budapest at 
 agergely@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Gavin Serkin at 
